"text": "

 

The above Node title has been inserted a second time using a bigger h2 size.  Ha!

Basic text entry is WYSIWYG. 

Even complex phrases such as...

Let's go down to the river, he yelled, and throw sticks in the water!

...work just as you write them.

Plus there are more editing options than we had with the original editor.

You can add a lot of usual style editing, such as highlighted stuff, direct from the node editor. Bold, underlined, italics, superscript, colored text are all easy to insert on the fly now.

You can use the standard Headings, as you would expect.

Heading1

Heading2

Heading3

Heading4

Heading5

All this you can do with the built-in editor. But these are just HTML pages, so you can also insert all sorts of clever web page stuff if you want. We will have other examples on that kind of thing coming soon. 

 

",

"text": "[[CONST:"NodeName"]]

This improved editor now allows us to do some cool stuff like this.

Using linked micro-services, we can call the CURIOS video mashup service from the OLab3 server and embed it into our OLab4 scenario seamlessly.

This clip shows a segment of this YouTube video, starting at 60secs and ending at 1:25 secs.

And now we continue where we left off with the next piece of the scenario. Cool eh?

",

"info": "

http://www.morguefile.com/archive/display/73220

",

"text": "

Of course, you can do the usual things with image files and sound files that you could do with OLab2 and OLab3. For example, this is an image attached to this case. 

[[MR:8]]

You can also embed the image directly from a web site, as long as the link leads to the picture:

Other media playing options are available now.

We can also refer to the above image using a named link. e.g. [[MR:"Start button"]] instead of using an index number. This makes it easier to remember when reusing Objects.

",

"text": "

Avatars are cartoon-like charicatures that bring a small degree of increased engagement for your learners. 

Previously these were created using Adobe Flash® animation. However, many platforms do not support this eg. iPad, iPhone.

So in OLab3, we implemented this entirely in HTML5 which is more up to date and broadly compatible.

At present, we have chosen not to include them in the current versions. There are now more powerful ways to create such figures.

In future, these will be supported via a plug-in module. If you would like to contribute to this effort, please contact us.

",

"text": "

[[CONST:"NodeName"]]

Well you made it to the end!

[[MR:6]] THE END.

",

"text": "

Counters are like variables in a computing language. They can be used to keep score but also to affect how the labyrinth case plays out, or what choices are given to the user. 

Note how the Counters below have changed in value already. For example, the temp has risen from 36.9 to [[CR:Temp]] -- things are getting hot!

This also demonstrates how Counter values can be a wide range of things: integers, floating point numbers and strings are the usual types.

Feel free to comment on this aspect here…

[[QU:GenFeedback]]

You can also alter Counters by attaching them to Questions. 

Both of the following Questions dynamically alter the 'Score' Counter.

This one alters the 'MyScore' Counter in big jumps.

[[QU:OLabUseful]]
[[QU:LearnerLevel]]

You can even place another
column of text to the right of these Questions

This closest Question alters the MyScore counter in small increments.

[[COUNTERS]]",

"text": "

Counters are a simple way of keeping track of progress for learners, providing them with additional forms of feedback, or providing a game-like element. 

In the generic OpenLabyrinth layout, you will see them down in the lower right corner of the screen. As they change, OLab also attempts to show you how your score changed. 

You can now embed a Counter value anywhere in the page, using either its ID number e.g. 101, which has a value of: [[CR:101]], or by using its name eg. 'MyScore', which should also show the same value: [[CR:"MyScore"]]. Either will work.

Counters can now also support text strings, which provides authors with more flexibility.  See the Counter below named 'Completed', which has a value of: [[CR:"Completed"]].

[[COUNTERS]]",

"text": "

As well as navigating a case, you can also ask more standard types of questions as you go. This is similar to a full survey tool like SurveyMonkey, but OLab can do so much more. 

You can simply collect text, perhaps asking them to reflect on some key element of the case.

[[QU:HowUse]]

Click on one of the links below. Your comments will be saved when you leave this node. 

You can also use pick lists and MCQs in the usual fashion. See [[LINK:4815]] for more information about this. 

You can also use the Question responses to change how the map behaves, using Counters and Rules. This makes OLab very powerful.

",
